To fetch a URL and wait for the content to load before continuing with the rest of your code, you can use the Promise-based `fetch()` method in combination with the `async/await` syntax. Here's an example code snippet:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Fetch URL and wait for content</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="content"></div>
    <script>
        async function fetchContent() {
            const response = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1');
            const data = await response.json();
            return data.title;
        }

        async function displayContent() {
            const title = await fetchContent();
            document.getElementById('content').textContent = title;
        }

        displayContent();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Explanation:

1. The `fetchContent()` function uses the `fetch()` method to fetch the content from the URL and then converts the response to a JSON object.

2. The `fetchContent()` function returns the `title` property of the JSON object.

3. The `displayContent()` function calls the `fetchContent()` function and waits for it to resolve using the `await` keyword.

4. The `title` variable is then used to set the text content of the HTML element with the ID `content`.

5. Finally, the `displayContent()` function is called to execute everything.

By using `async/await`, the code ensures that the content is fully loaded and available before proceeding with the rest of the code.

